-- Aviva, BG Group, BHP, BP, Lloyds: U.K., Irish Equity Preview
-- B y   B e n   M a r t i n   a n d   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 2010-11-02T07:55:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-01/bg-group-bp-imperial-tobacco-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  climbed 19.46, or 0.3 percent,
to 5,694.62. The FTSE All-Share Index also rose 0.3 percent and
Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  fell 0.2 percent.  Allied Irish Banks Plc  (ALBK ID): Shareholders have
approved the lender’s sale of its 22.4 percent stake in U.S.-
based M&T Bank Corp. Allied Irish said progress on the disposal
of its U.K. business has been challenging and it will keep the
sales process under review. The shares added 0.9 percent to 34
cents in Dublin.  Aviva Plc  (AV/ LN): The U.K.’s second-biggest insurer
reported a 5 percent rise in sales for the first nine months to
35.9 million pounds ($57.67 million). The shares fell 0.1
percent to 397.6 pence.  BG Group Plc  (BG/ LN): The U.K.’s third-biggest oil and gas
producer reported a 12 percent rise in third-quarter profit to
$876 million. The shares fell 0.4 percent to 1,210.5 pence.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BLT LN): Canadian officials responsible
for reviewing BHP’s hostile offer for Potash Corp. of
Saskatchewan Inc. are proposing the government accept the
transaction with certain conditions attached, the National Post
reported, citing unidentified people within the ruling
Conservative Party. BHP’s shares rose 1 percent to 2,235 pence.  BP Plc  (BP/ LN): the company responsible for the biggest
oil spill in U.S. history said profit fell 66 percent after
taking a further pre-tax charge of $7.7 billion related to the
Gulf of Mexico spill.  Third-quarter net income dropped to $1.79 billion from
$5.34 billion in the year-earlier period, London-based BP said
today in a statement. The stock fell 0.4 percent to 424 pence.  Imperial Tobacco Group Plc  (IMT LN): The maker of Davidoff
cigarettes more than doubled full-year net income to 1.51
billion pound, beating the average analyst estimate of 1.42
billion. The shares fell 0.1 percent to 1,997 pence.  Legal & General Group Plc  (LGEN LN): The U.K.’s fourth-
biggest insurer named Nick Prettejohn as an independent non-
executive director. Frances Heaton, a non-executive director of
the group since July 2001, is retiring. The stock fell 0.2
percent to 100.2 pence.  Lloyds Banking Group Plc  (LLOY LN): The U.K.’s largest
mortgage lender said it expects to report a “good” financial
performance for the full-year. The bank also reported a decline
in impairments in the third quarter. The shares gained 1 percent
to 69.6 pence.  Reckitt Benckiser Group Plc  (RB/ LN): The world’s biggest
maker of household cleaners reported third-quarter net income of
426 million pounds, beating analyst’ median estimate of 405.1
million pounds. Sales for the period reached 2.11 billion
pounds. The shares advanced 1 percent to 3,525 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
